{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505863"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:37:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:37:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2493"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2493"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.62,0.05,0.25,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79070"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2493"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64422"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1218"},{"type":"tags","id":"1219"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"1546"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42506"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79070"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents with painful ulcers on his scalp. The ulcers began as small \u0022blood blisters\u0022 two weeks ago, possibly developing after accidentally knocking his head on a low-lying door. He recalls several months ago having had a large ulcer on his leg develop in similar circumstances after minimal trauma - this ulcer on his leg has only just healed. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes which is managed with metformin and has always been well controlled. He denies a history of skin cancer. He is a retired mechanic, smokes 15 cigarettes a day and drinks several cans of beer on weekends. There is no history of travel. He feels systemically well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there are two large full-thickness ulcers across the right scalp. The ulcers have purple margins with undermined edges. The surrounding skin appears normal. On the leg at the site of the previous ulcer, a cribriform scar is noted. There is no evidence of any peripheral neuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESwab microscopy, culture and sensitivity is unremarkable. The edge of one of the ulcers is biopsied and reveales a neutrophilic infiltrate with no evidence of infection or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Crohn\u0027s disease","Pyoderma gangrenosum","Squamous cell carcinoma","Diabetic ulcers","Pseudomonas infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyoderma gangrenosum (PG)\u003C/strong\u003E is a painful cutaneous ulcerative condition that is included in the group of neutrophilic dermatoses. It may affect any body site but does have a predilection for the lower limbs. It often develops at a site of minor trauma. Characteristically the full-thickness ulcer has an undermined edge which is purple in colour. PG is not an infection, nor does it involve gangrene. Aetiology is poorly understood but is believed to be due to immune system dysregulation and genetic variations. Other neutrophilic dermatoses include Sweets syndrome, neutrophilic dermatosis of the dorsal hands, Behcet disease and bowel-associated-dermatitis-arthritis syndrome. PG is a diagnosis of exclusion - other causes of ulceration including infection, malignancy, vasculitis, diabetes and trauma need to be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can manifest as extra-gastrointestinal ulceration, however, sites commonly affected are the trunk, arms and legs. Histology of cutaneous Crohn\u0027s would reveal a granulomatous infiltrate. Inflammatory bowel disease is also associated with PG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECutaneous malignancy like \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an important differential for chronic ulceration, particularly on the scalp. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of ulcers, typically occurring on the lower legs. In the absence of any peripheral neuropathy, diabetes is less likely to be the cause of this man\u0027s current problems. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfection\u003C/strong\u003E may be a cause of ulcers or occur within chronic ulceration and then impair healing. In this case, the clinical scenario points to the diagnosis of PG, with the histopathology excluding malignancy and wound swabs negative. If it was felt these conditions were clinically more likely, consider sampling error of investigations and repeat with representative samples.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pyoderma gangrenosum is a painful cutaneous ulcerative condition that is a diagnosis of exclusion.","Pyoderma gangrenosum often develops at sites of minor trauma and is characterised by ulcers with undermined, purple edges."],"references":["Ahn C, Negus D, Huang W. Pyoderma gangrenosum: a review of pathogenesis and treatment. Expert Rev Clin Immunol. 2018 Mar;14(3):225-233. doi: 10.1080/1744666X.2018.1438269. Epub 2018 Feb 13. PMID: 29406827. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29406827/","Rodr\u00edguez-Z\u00fa\u00f1iga MJM, Heath MS, Gontijo JRV, Ortega-Loayza AG. Pyoderma gangrenosum: a review with special emphasis on Latin America literature. An Bras Dermatol. 2019 Nov-Dec;94(6):729-743. doi: 10.1016/j.abd.2019.06.001. Epub 2019 Nov 1. PMID: 31789268; PMCID: PMC6939079. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6939079/","Ormerod AD, Hampton PJ. Rook\u2019s Textbook of Dermatology \u2013 Neutrophilic Dermatoses, 9th edn. Christopher Griffiths, Jonathan Barker, Tanya Bleiker, Robert Chalmers, Daniel Creamer, eds. Publisher: Wiley\u2010Blackwell, 2016; 4696 pp. ISBN: 978\u20101118441190."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64422"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2493"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20085"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20085"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ac2c7670-0bf2-4eca-8244-eb361882452c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ac2c7670-0bf2-4eca-8244-eb361882452c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64422"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T14:29:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T14:30:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2493"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79070"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id